                <div class="accordion-body">
                    <h4 class="fw-bold">What is Fire Safety?</h4>
                    <p>
                        Fire safety refers to the set of precautions, procedures, and measures taken to prevent fires,
                        minimize the risk of fire-related accidents,
                        and ensure the safety of individuals and property in the event of a fire. It involves a
                        combination of awareness, preparedness, and proper
                        safety practices to prevent fires from occurring and mitigate their impact if they do happen.
                    </p>

                    <h4 class="fw-bold mt-4">Fire Hazards to Look Out For</h4>
                    <p>
                        It's crucial to know the fire hazards to look out for. This can help organizations and
                        individuals take proactive measures and create an
                        effective fire safety system.
                    </p>

                    <ul class="text-start mx-auto" style="max-width: 750px;">
                        <li><strong>Electrical hazards</strong> – faulty wiring, overloaded circuits, damaged cords,
                            malfunctioning equipment</li>
                        <li><strong>Cooking-related hazards</strong> – grease buildup, unattended cooking, misuse of
                            appliances</li>
                        <li><strong>Heating sources</strong> – unsafe use of heaters, fireplaces, wood-burning stoves
                        </li>
                        <li><strong>Flammable liquids and chemicals</strong> – gasoline, paint thinners, solvents</li>
                        <li><strong>Smoking</strong> – careless cigarette disposal</li>
                        <li><strong>Open flames</strong> – unattended candles, incense</li>
                        <li><strong>Flammable materials</strong> – paper, cardboard, textiles, gases</li>
                    </ul>

                    <img src="https://mycalcas.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Home-Fire-Safety-Guide.png"
                        alt="Fire Safety Guide" class="img-fluid my-4 rounded shadow"
                        style="max-width: 70%; height: auto;" />

                    <h4 class="fw-bold mt-4">What to Do During a Fire</h4>
                    <p>
                        During a fire, it’s crucial to act quickly and follow proper procedures. These tips can help
                        guide you:
                    </p>

                    <ul class="text-start mx-auto" style="max-width: 750px;">
                        <li><strong>Alert others</strong> – Activate an alarm or shout “Fire!”</li>
                        <li><strong>Evacuate safely</strong> – Use designated routes; avoid hot doors</li>
                        <li><strong>Crawl low if necessary</strong> – Stay below smoke level</li>
                        <li><strong>Close doors behind you</strong> – Helps slow spread of fire</li>
                        <li><strong>Use stairs, not elevators</strong> – Elevators are dangerous during fire</li>
                        <li><strong>Stay calm</strong> – Keep yourself and others focused</li>
                        <li><strong>Follow emergency protocols</strong> – Listen to instructions</li>
                        <li><strong>Help those in need</strong> – If safe, assist others</li>
                        <li><strong>Do not re-enter the building</strong> – Wait for official clearance</li>
                        <li><strong>Call emergency services</strong> – Once in a safe location</li>
                    </ul>

                    <img src="https://www.fireprosafetysolutions.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/fire-saty.jpg"
                        alt="Fire Safety Response" class="img-fluid my-4 rounded shadow"
                        style="max-width: 100%; height: auto;" />

                    <p class="mt-4">
                        Explore further guides from the
                        <a href="https://www.redcross.org/get-help/how-to-prepare-for-emergencies/types-of-emergencies/fire.html"
